 is to provide a comprehensive overview and descriptive generalizations of major phonetic and phonological phenomena in modern Japanese by reviewing important studies in the fields over the past century. It also presents a summary of interesting questions that remain unsolved in the literature. The volume consists of eighteen chapters in addition to an introduction to the whole volume. In addition to providing descriptive generalizations of empirical phonetic/phonological facts, this volume also aims to give an overview of major phonological theories including, but not restricted to, traditional generative phonology, lexical phonology, prosodic morphology, intonational phonology, and the more recent Optimality Theory. It also touches on theories of speech perception and production. This book serves as a comprehensive guide to Japanese phonetics and phonology for all interested in linguistics and speech sciences.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aJapanese.  aPhonetics.  aPhonology.1 aFujimoto, Masako, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirata, Yukari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIgarashi, Yosuke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIshihara, Shinichiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIto, Junko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKageyama, Taro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawagoe, Itsue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawahara, Shigeto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKubozono, Haruo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators